__NoSQL embedded database__ is very great and simple database for small projects. It can help you with storing contact forms, emails, logs, etc.. Each NoSQL database is separated file, the database contains serialized JSON data.

Try: [__NoSQL & Table embedded database explorer__](https://nosql.totaljs.com)

```javascript
// If you use Total.js
var nosql = NOSQL('users');
// or
var nosql = DB('users'); // is same as NOSQL but NOSQL() will work with e.g. SQL Agent.

// +v2.8.0
// READ-ONLY MODE, reads/streams DB from URL
var nosql = DB('https://www.totaljs.com/test.nosql');

// If you use require('nosql'):
var DB = require('nosql');
var nosql = DB.load('/path/to/database/file.nosql');
```

__Good to know__:

- __supports joins__
- DB reads `32` kB blocks of data per read
- boolean `true` values are added with empty space as `"key":true ,` because it's more effective for updating of DB file
- modified data can start with `-` char and DB performs a cleaner of DB file after some time (within 24 hours, you can change this behaviour in the `config` file: `nosql-cleaner`) for useless data

### WARNING

Each document __in DB file__ must end with `\n` __newline char__. This is very important rule!

__Bad__:

```html
{"field":"value"}\n
{"field":"value"}
```

__Good__:

```html
{"field":"value"}\n
{"field":"value"}\n
```

methods.body:
Inserts a document into the database.

```javascript
NOSQL('newsletter').insert({ email: 'petersirka@gmail.com' });

// Or unique record:
NOSQL('newsletter').insert({ email: 'petersirka@gmail.com' }, true).where('email', 'petersirka@gmail.com');```

Streams documents from database.

```javascript
NOSQL('users').stream(function(doc, repository) {
	repository.max = repository.max ? Math.max(repository.max, doc.age) : doc.age;
	repository.min = repository.min ? Math.min(repository.min, doc.age) : doc.age;
}, { max: null, min: null }, function(err, repository, count) {
	console.log(repository);
	console.log('Count of processed documents:', count);
});```

Creates a filter automatically according to the __Total.js Schema__. Query parameters will be used for the filtering and parameters:

- `fields` (separated by comma) will be returned from DB
- `page` will be used as a page
- `limit` will be used as a limit otherwise `def_maxlimit`
- `sort` will be used for __sorting__ otherwise `def_sort`

```javascript
// builder.autofill($, allowedfields, skipfields, def_sort, def_maxlimit);
// @$ {SchemaOptions} Instance of SchemaOptions
// @allowedfields {String} Optional, can contain fields not defined in the schema and must be separated by comma ","
// @skippedfields {String} Optional, can contain skip fields defined in schema and must be separated by comma ","
// @def_sort {String} Optional, default sort in the form "FIELDNAME_asc" or "FIELDNAME_desc"
// @def_maxlimit {Number} Optional, a maximum count of items per page
// @localized {String} Optional, defines localized name of fields
// returns QueryBuilder

// IMPORTANT:
// If "def_maxlimit" is not defined then the pagination isnt't applied

// Example:
db.find('users').autofill($, 'dtcreated:Date,dtupdated:Date', 'id', 'dtcreated_desc', 50);

// Example with localized fields:
db.find('users').autofill($, 'dtcreated:Date,dtupdated:Date', 'id', 'dtcreated_desc', 50, 'name,description').language('sk');
```

Locks all DB operations.

```javascript
NOSQL('products').lock(function(next) {
	// Locks all DB operations for 5 seconds
	setTimeout(next, 5000);
});```

Inserts a document into the database.

```javascript
TABLE('newsletter').insert({ email: 'petersirka@gmail.com' });

// Or unique record:
TABLE('newsletter').insert({ email: 'petersirka@gmail.com' }, true).where('email', 'petersirka@gmail.com');```

Streams documents from database.

```javascript
TABLE('users').stream(function(doc, repository) {
	repository.max = repository.max ? Math.max(repository.max, doc.age) : doc.age;
	repository.min = repository.min ? Math.min(repository.min, doc.age) : doc.age;
}, { max: null, min: null }, function(err, repository, count) {
	console.log(repository);
	console.log('Count of processed documents:', count);
});```

Locks all DB operations.

```javascript
TABLE('products').lock(function(next) {
	// Locks all DB operations for 5 seconds
	setTimeout(next, 5000);
});```

api.body:
__NoSQL Database Builder__ helps with building queries for classic CRUD operation. A lot of methods from `Database` implementation returns this `DatabaseBuilder`.

```javascript
var nosql = NOSQL('users');

nosql.find().make(function(builder) {
    builder.between('age', 20, 30);
    builder.callback(function(err, response) {
        console.log('users between 20 and 30 years:', response);
    });
});

nosql.insert({ id: 3499, age: 55, name: 'Peter' }).callback(function(err) {
    console.log('The user has been created.');
});

nosql.update({ id: 3403, age: 60, name: 'Lucia' }).make(function(builder) {
    // builder.first(); --> updates only the one document
    builder.where('id', 3403);
    builder.callback(function(err, count) {
        console.log('updated documents:', count);
    });
});

nosql.modify({ age: 58 }).make(function(builder) {
    // builder.first(); --> modifies only the one document
    builder.where('id', 3403);
    builder.callback(function(err, count) {
        console.log('modified documents:', count);
    });
});

nosql.remove().make(function(builder) {
    // builder.first(); --> removes only the one document
    builder.where('age', '<', 15);
    builder.callback(function(err, count) {
        console.log('removed documents:', count);
    });
});```

methods.body:
Evaluates a rule for each document. It other words: improved creating of conditions

```javascript
builder.rule(doc => doc.age > 33);
// or builder.builder.rule((doc, param) => doc.age > param.age, { age: 33 });```

Creates `or`.

```javascript
builder.or()
builder.where('age', 30);
builder.where('age', 50);
builder.where('age', 70);
builder.end();```

Creates `and`. This `and()` is a default scope for all conditions.

```javascript
builder.and()
builder.where('price', 100);
builder.where('isdiscount', true);
builder.where('idmerchant', 343);
builder.end();

// out of "and":
scopebuilder.where('isremoved', false);```

Joins another database - it performs `LEFT JOIN`. `DatabaseBuilder.join()` returns a new instance of DatabaseBuilder and a bit modified. __IMPORTANT__ joins can't be used for updating/removing operations.

### One to One

```javascript
var builder = NOSQL('orders').find();
builder.where('paid', true);
builder.take(10);
builder.callback(function(err, docs) {
	// Orders
	console.log(docs);
});

var join = builder.join('user', 'users');
// users.id === orders.userid
join.on('id', 'userid');

// we want only the one document (not array)
join.first();
```

### One to Many

```javascript
var builder = NOSQL('users').find();
builder.take(10);
builder.callback(function(err, docs) {
	// Users with orders
	console.log(docs);
});

var join = builder.join('orders', 'orders');
// orders.id === users.userid
join.on('userid', 'id');

// Orders must be paid
join.where('paid', true);
```

### Scalar operations

__We want to know count of orders per user__:

```javascript
var builder = NOSQL('users').find();
builder.take(10);
builder.callback(function(err, docs) {
	// Users
	console.log(docs);
});

var join = builder.join('orders', 'orders');
// orders.id === users.userid
join.on('userid', 'id');
join.scalar('count');
```

__We want to know a max. price from orders per user__:

```javascript
var builder = NOSQL('users').find();
builder.take(10);
builder.callback(function(err, docs) {
	// Users
	console.log(docs);
});

var join = builder.join('orders', 'orders');
// orders.id === users.userid
join.on('userid', 'id');
join.scalar('max', 'price');
```

__We want to know a min. price from orders per user__:

```javascript
var builder = NOSQL('users').find();
builder.take(10);
builder.callback(function(err, docs) {
	// Users
	console.log(docs);
});

var join = builder.join('orders', 'orders');
// orders.id === users.userid
join.on('userid', 'id');
join.scalar('min', 'price');
```

__We want to know a avg. price from orders per user__:

```javascript
var builder = NOSQL('users').find();
builder.take(10);
builder.callback(function(err, docs) {
	// Users
	console.log(docs);
});

var join = builder.join('orders', 'orders');
// orders.id === users.userid
join.on('userid', 'id');
join.scalar('avg', 'price');
```

__Good to know__: `INNER JOIN` is not supported.

### Joining between NOSQL and TABLE

```javascript
TABLE('users').find().join('data', NOSQL('usersdata')).on('userid', 'id');

// OR vice versa

NOSQL('users').find().join('data', TABLE('usersdata')).on('userid', 'id');
```

Creates a projection for properties, otherwise: the database selects only these fields.

__Projection__:

```javascript
NOSQL('yourdb').find().fields('id', 'name').callback(console.log);
// Fields "id" and "name" will be in the result
```

__A reverse projection__:

```javascript
NOSQL('yourdb').find().fields('-id', '-name').callback(console.log);
// Fields "id" and "name" will be removed from the result```

Returns promise for async/await operation.

```javascript
async function data() {
	var response = await NOSQL('users').find().promise();
	console.log(response);
}

data();```

This method executes a provided function once for each document in DB. __IMPORTANT__: don't use variables external references.

```javascript
builder.each(function(doc, repository) {
	repository.max = Math.max(repository.max || 0, doc.price);
}).callback(function(err, response, count, repository) {
	console.log(repository.max);
});
```

This method works with `update` and `modify` DB operations.

```javascript
var user = {};
user.id = 100;
user.name = 'Peter';

NOSQL('users').update(user, true).where('id', user.id).insert(function(doc) {
	// user not found
	// doc == is document for update (doc == user)
	doc.datecreated = new Date();
});```

A DatabaseBuilder maker and it creates a DatabaseBuilder function scope.

```javascript
var nosql = NOSQL('users');

nosql.find().make(function(builder) {
    builder.between('age', 20, 30);
    builder.take(10);
});```

api.body:
`+v3.0.0` __NoSQL Database Storage__ is an engine for storing small big data. It can store documents to independent database files divided by days. In other words: __storage__ creates each day a new database. File name of database is in the form: `yyyyMMdd.nosql` and each database has own `storage` directory. __IMPORTANT__: storage can't update/remove documents, it supports append/read mode only.

```javascript
var storage = NOSQL('yourdbname').storage;
// or
var storage = NOSQLSTORAGE('yourdbname');

// Example of inserting
storage.insert({ your: 'data' });
```

`+v3.1.0` supports very effective filtering documents outside of main thread. You can filter documents with help of `.find()`, `.scalar()` and `.count()` methods and you can set count of threads for reading.

methods.body:
Finds documents according to the filter.

```javascript
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').find('2018')
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').find('2018-05')
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').find('2018-10-10')
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').find(null, '2019');
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').find(null, null, 10);

NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').find('2018', '2019', 5).where('sensorid', '00-04-a3-0b-00-1e-14-be').take(100).sort('temperature', true).callback(console.log);```

Counts documents according to the filter.

```javascript
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').count('2018')
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').count('2018-05')
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').count('2018-10-10')
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').count(null, '2019');
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').count(null, null, 10);

NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').count('2018', '2019', 5).where('sensorid', '00-04-a3-0b-00-1e-14-be').callback(console.log);```

Performs a scalar operation according to the filter.

```javascript
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scalar('2018', null, 'max', 'temperature')
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scalar('2018-05', null, 'min', 'temperature')
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scalar('2018-10-10')
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scalar(null, '2019', 'avg', 'temperature');
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scalar(null, null, 'max', 'temperature', 10);

NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scalar('2018', '2019', 'max', 'temperature', 5).where('sensorid', '00-04-a3-0b-00-1e-14-be').callback(console.log);```

Scans all documents from newest to latest.

```javascript
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scan('2018', function(doc, repository) { ... }
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scan('2018-05', function(doc, repository) { ... }
// NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scan('2018-10-10', function(doc, repository) { ... }

NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').scan('2018', '2019', function(doc, repository) {
	repository.max = repository.max ? Math.max(repository.max, doc.temperature) : doc.temperature;
	repository.min = repository.min ? Math.min(repository.min, doc.temperature) : doc.temperature;
}, function(err, repository) {
	console.log('Max. temperature: ', repository.max);
	console.log('Min. temperature: ', repository.min);
});
```

__MapReduce__ function can perform effective processing of new documents in NoSQL embedded storage. At first `MapReduce` scans all documents in the storage and then is the `MapReduce` function used only for new documents. Results (called `repository`) from `MapReduce` are stored in file, so it's persistent.

- if the `MapReduce` is registered at the first time the storage scans all documents immediately

```javascript
NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').mapreduce('count', function(doc, repository) {
	repository.count = (repository.count || 0) + 1;

	// FOR UNDERSTANDING, doesn't use this:
	console.log('count');

});

NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').mapreduce('minmax', function(doc, repository) {

	repository.min = repository.min ? Math.min(repository.min, doc.temperature) : doc.temperature;
	repository.max = repository.max ? Math.max(repository.max, doc.temperature) : doc.temperature;

	// FOR UNDERSTANDING, doesn't use this:
	console.log('minmax');
});

NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').insert({ temperature: 23.4 });
// Output in console:
// count
// minmax

NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').insert({ temperature: 25.4 });
// Output in console:
// count
// minmax
```

This method reads stats from MapReduce repository.

```javascript
NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').stats('count', function(err, repository) {
	console.log(repository);
});

NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').stats('minmax', function(err, repository) {
	console.log(repository);
});

NOSQLSTORAGE('iot').stats(function(err, repository) {
	// All stats from all MapReduce results
	// @repository {Object}
	console.log(repository);
});
```

api.body:
__NoSQL Database Counter__ helps with creating stats for number of views or downloads.

```javascript
var database = NOSQL('blog');

