api.body:
Total.js Cluster `+v2.6.0` can clusterize a current app to multiple threads. Cluster tries to synchronize `cache` and `sessions` between all threads automatically and enables locking of NoSQL embedded database files.

### How to run Total.js Cluster?

```javascript
const options = {};
options.ip = '0.0.0.0';

// Run the framework in the cluster
require('total.js').cluster.http(4, 'release', options);
```

## Auto-elasticity

`+v3.4.0` The framework automatically adapts performance to application needs. In 5 seconds interval it pings each thread and if the respond of all threads is more than 70ms then it opens a new thread.

```javascript
const options = {};
options.ip = '0.0.0.0';
options.max = 100; // a maximum count of open threads (default: infinite)

require('total.js').cluster.http('auto', 'release', options);
```

## Watcher in debug mode

`+v3.4.0` supports watcher in `debug` clustered mode. If the framework will capture a change then it restarts each thread.

```javascript
const options = {};
options.ip = '0.0.0.0';

// Run the framework in the cluster
require('total.js').cluster.http('auto', 'debug', options);
```

## Threads

`+v3.4.0` Supports threads. More details in [Thread section](#pages~Threads).

```javascript
const options = {};
options.ip = '0.0.0.0';

// IMPORTANT:
options.thread = 'THREAD_NAME';
// it's targeted to:
// /yourapp/threads/THREAD_NAME/

require('total.js').cluster.http('auto', 'release', options);
```

## Good to know

`+v3.4.0` Cluster watches a current working directory. If it will contain a file called `restart` then it restarts threads (then will be the file removed). It will work with threads too, just create a file called `restart_THREAD_NAME`.

methods.body:
Registers a response for all requests with the same `name` identifier.

__Example__:

```javascript
F.custer.response('sum', function(value, next) {
    var newvalue = value + 1;
    // We have to call a "next" function for delivery of a new value
    next(newvalue);    
});```

Creates a request for all cluster instances. Application has to have registered `F.cluster.response()`. A response of the request is `Object Array` because this array contains values from each thread of applications with except of caller application.

__Example__:

```javascript
F.custer.request('sum', 100, function(err, value) {

    var sum = 0;

    for (var i = 0, length = value.length; i < length; i++)
        sum += value[i];

    console.log(sum);
});```

__Only for master process__. This method registers an event in `master` process.

__Example__:

```javascript
F.custer.on('event', function(data) {
    console.log(data);
});
```

api.body:
`+v2.9.0` supports a connection via WebSocket from Total.js as a __client__. Implementation is very simple and you need to use a global method `WEBSOCKETCLIENT(callback)` for creating a new client. __For example:__

```javascript
WEBSOCKETCLIENT(function(client) {

    client.connect('ws://127.0.0.1:8000/');

    client.on('open', function() {
        console.log('OPEN');
    });

    client.on('close', function() {
        console.log('CLOSE');
    });

    client.on('message', function(message) {
        console.log('MESSAGE', message);
    });

    // Default options:
    // client.options.type = 'json';
    // client.options.compress = true;
    // client.options.reconnect = 3000;
    // client.options.encodedecode = true;

    // Sending:
    // client.send({ some: 'object' });

});
```

properties.body:
Contains a client options, default values:

```javascript
client.options.type = 'json';
// {String}
// default: "json"
// Type of communication
// Can contain these values: "json", "binary" (ArrayBuffer) or "text" (Plain text)

client.options.compress = true;
// {Boolean}
// default: true
// Enables WebSocket deflate compression

client.options.reconnect = 3000;
// {Number} in milliseconds
// default: 3000
// Time for re-open closed connection

client.options.encodedecode = true;
// {Boolean}
// default: true
// This option performs encodeURIComponent()/decodeURIComponent() for "json" and "text" values automatically
// It solves a problem with UTF-8 encoding on the client-side
```

