api.body:
`+v3.3.0` Preferences are a special functionality which can read and store data persistently. They are targeted for applications where the users can change some preferences.

__Writing data__:

```javascript
PREF.set('key_string', 'value');
PREF.set('key_number', 102);
PREF.set('key_boolean', true);
PREF.set('key_date', new Date());
```

Data will be stored on HDD into the file: `databases/preferences.json`. If the framework will be restarted then the data will be loaded into the memory again.

__Reading data__:

```javascript
console.log(PREF.key_string);
console.log(PREF.key_number);
console.log(PREF.key_boolean);
console.log(PREF.key_date);
```

### Good to know

Framework automatically stores preferences into the file `databases/preferences.json`, but you can rewrite writing/reading preferences. Just create some definition file with your custom implementation of preferences:

```javascript
// This delegate is executed when the framework is loading
F.onPrefLoad = function(next) {
	// your operations
	// here you can load preferences from some storages
	next({});
};

// This delegate is executed when the framework is loading
F.onPrefSave = function(preferences) {
	// your operations
	// here you need to store preferences to some storages
};
```

`+v3.3.0` Session can help with reading/storing session data. __Read carefully__ the documentation below because __session item__ contains two identifiers `id` and `sessionid` which is very important to know difference between each other.

```javascript
// A default session is initialized
var session = SESSION();

// OR with a specific storage called "orders":
// var orders = SESSION('orders');

// OR with a specific storage called "tokens":
// var tokens = SESSION('tokens');
```

### Session item object

```javascript
// SESSION ITEM:
{
	id: 'user_id',                             // A main identifier, for example "user.id"
	sessionid: 'session_id',                   // Must be always unique, we use "UID()"
	expire: 'EXPIRATION_DATE',                 // Expiration date, when will the session expire?
	created: 'CREATION_DATE',                  // Internal value
	settings: 'custom settings (optional)',    // It's targeted for specific situations only, so this field can contain special settings (must be STRING!!!)
	note: 'a custom note (optional)'           // Here we can store for example parsed User-Agent (browser name + device type)

	// SESSION DATA:
	data: { SESSION: 'DATA' },                 // A session data, for example in most cases contains a user profile
}
```

- the framework stores on HDD only these fields `id`, `sessionid`, `note`, `settings`, `expire`, `created`
- `data` can be null and when data is null then the `Session` instance tries to load data via `instance.ondata` delegate
- session DB can contain several same `session.id` in DB but `sessionid` will be unique per each `session.id`

### Good to know

- by default are sessions stored in plain-text files in `databases` directory in the form `sessions_NAME.txt`
- session item contains last usage time, creation date, custom note and custom settings, these info can be very helpful in several cases
- `+v3.4.0` enables auto-clearing of unused sessions (can be disable via `allow_sessions_unused` option)

properties.body:
A delegate which must contain a function which returns a session data according to the session item. This delegate is executed only when __session data__ has been released or unused or not loaded.

```javacript
var session = SESSION();

session.ondata = function(meta, next) {

	// meta {Object}                      === Session item
	// next {Function(err, sessiondata)}  === A callback which must be called

	// A quick example with DBMS module
	DBMS().read('tbl_user').where('id', meta.id).callback(next);
};```

methods.body:
Creates a session and stores the identifier in the cookie. The example below describes possibilities:

```javascript
var $ = SCHEMAOPTIONS_OR_OPERATIONOPTIONS_OR_CONTROLLER;

// Options
var opt = {};
opt.name = 'auth';             // A cookie name
opt.key = CONF.authkey;        // A cookie secret key
opt.id = user.id;              // A user ID
opt.expire = '3 days';         // Expiration
opt.data = user;               // A session data
// opt.sessionid = UID()       // Optional, a unique session ID (default: UID())
// opt.options = {};           // Optional, A cookie options (default: { httponly: true, security: 'lax' })
// opt.strict = true;          // Optional, a strict comparing of cookie value according to user-agent combined with IP address (default: false)
// opt.settings = '';          // Optional, custom session settings
opt.note = ($.headers['user-agent'] || '').parseUA() + ' ({0})'.format($.ip); // A custom note

// Creates a cookie and session item
SESSION().setcookie($.controller, opt, $.done());
```

Reads a session according to the cookie value. The example below describes usage with `AUTH()` delegate.

```javascript
AUTH(function($) {
	// Options
	var opt = {};
	opt.name = 'auth';             // A cookie name
	opt.key = 'key_1984';          // An encrypt key
	opt.expire = '3 days';         // Optional, after read can be updated expiration
	// opt.extendcookie = true;    // Extends cookie expiration (default: true)
	// opt.removecookie = true;    // Removes cookie if isn't valid (default: true)
	// opt.options = {};           // Optional, a cookie options when the the cookie is extended (default: { httponly: true, security: 'lax' })
	// opt.ddos = 5;               // Optional, enables a simple protection for max. 5 attempts of hijacking of the cookie value (allowed for only the one IP and IP can be blocked for 15 minutes)

	// Reads a cookie and session
	SESSION().getcookie($.controller, opt, $.done());
});
```

Creates a session token which can be used as a custom header like `x-token`. The example below describes possibilities:

```javascript
var $ = SCHEMAOPTIONS_OR_OPERATIONOPTIONS_OR_CONTROLLER;

// Options
var opt = {};
opt.name = 'auth';             // A cookie name
opt.key = CONF.authkey;        // A cookie secret key
opt.id = user.id;              // A user ID
opt.expire = '3 days';         // Expiration
opt.data = user;               // A session data
// opt.sessionid = UID()       // Optional, a unique session ID (default: UID())
// opt.strict = true;          // Optional, a strict comparing of cookie value according to user-agent combined with IP address (default: false)
// opt.settings = '';          // Optional, custom session settings
opt.note = ($.headers['user-agent'] || '').parseUA() + ' ({0})'.format($.ip); // A custom note

// Creates a cookie and session item
SESSION().settoken($.controller, opt, function(err, token, item, meta) {
	// now you can store "token" to response headers or somewhere else
	// "token" is needed for decrypting of value and must used with SESSION().gettoken()
});```

Reads a session according to the custom `token` and the `token` can be generated by the `session.settoken()` method. The example below describes usage with `AUTH()` delegate.

```javascript
AUTH(function($) {
	// Options
	var opt = {};
	opt.token = 'TOKEN_VALUE';     // A token
	opt.key = 'key_1984';          // An encrypt key
	opt.expire = '3 days';         // Optional, after read can be updated expiration
	// opt.ddos = 5;               // Optional, enables a simple protection for max. 5 attempts of hijacking of the token value (allowed for only the one IP and IP can be blocked for 15 minutes)

	// Reads a cookie and session
	SESSION().gettoken($.controller, opt, $.done());
});```

Evaluates a script in the secure scope. This method can handle user-defined scripts.

```javascript
// value
// next(newValue or error) --> this is a callback
// now() --> this method returns current datetime
SCRIPT('next(value + 1)', 5, function(err, value, argument) {
    // value === 6
    console.log(value);
});

// SCRIPT() evaluates code like this:
// function (value, next, now) {
//     SAFE
//     next(value + 1);
// }
```

### Precompile

```javascript
var fn = SCRIPT('next(value + 1)');
fn(10, (err, response) => console.log(response));
fn(20, (err, response) => console.log(response));
fn(30, (err, response) => console.log(response));```

Gets a route object.

```javascript
var route = ROUTING('GET /*', ['unauthorize']);
if (route) {
	route.execute = function() {
		// overwriting action
		// this === Controller
		this.plain('Response');
	};
}```

Creates a middleware. The middleware is executed before is executing a `Request`, `Controller`, or `Module`. The middleware has to be specified for usage.

```javascript
MIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware', function($) {

	// IMPORTANT: next processing
	// {Function}
	$.next();

	// Cancel processing
	// {Function}
	$.cancel();

	// HTTP Request
	// {Object}
	$.req;

	// HTTP response
	// {Object}
	$.res;

	// Route options (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.options;

	// Request body data (alias to req.body)
	// {Object}
	$.body;

	// URL query data (alias to req.query)
	// {Object}
	$.query;
	$.filter;

	// User instance (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.user;

	// Uploaded files (alias to req.files)
	// {Array Object}
	$.files;

	// Session instance (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.session;

	// +v3.3.0: A current session ID
	// {String}
	$.sessionid;

	// Language
	// {String}
	$.language;

	// Controller (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.controller;

	// Dynamic routing params (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.params;

	// First dynamic param
	// {String}
	$.id;

	// +v3.3.0: Alias to req.headers
	// {Object}
	$.headers;

	// +v3.4.0: Returns parsed User-Agent
	// {String}
	$.ua;

});
```

### How to cancel `next` processing? 

```javascript
MIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware', function($) {

	$.cancel();
	// or
	// $.next(false);

});
```

### Older and removed implementation

```javascript
MIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware'. function(req, res, next, options, controller) {
	next();
});```

Registers a new motificator.

```javascript
MODIFY(function(type, filename, value, controller) {
	// @type {String} can contain: "view", "style", "script", "static" (static files like html, js, script, style, markdown or plain-text files)
	// @filename {String} can be empty
	// @value {String} a content (view, JS, CSS, etc.)
	// @controller {Object} can be "undefined"

	// MUST RETURN (UPDATED) VALUE
	return value;
});
```

This is very helpful method for performing of application/database updates. The method tries to execute a script of each script of update in the order. If the file isn't located then update will be continue with another script. Scripts are running in main application thread. If you will perform an update in cluster mode then the "0" thread only will perform the update. This feature is a simple alternative to `startup` folder.

```javascript
// How does the framework perform that update?
// - tries to load a script /updates/1.0.1.js
// - tries to load a script /updates/1.0.2.js
// - tries to load a script /updates/1.0.3.js
UPDATE(['1.0.1', '1.0.2', '1.0.3'], function() {
	// DONE
}, 'Updating database');

// After update are files renamed to:
// - tries to load a script /updates/1.0.1.js-bk
// - tries to load a script /updates/1.0.2.js-bk
// - tries to load a script /updates/1.0.3.js-bk
// So after the next start will the scripts skipped.
```

Creates special incremented UUID, minimal output length is 17 chars, e.g. `16042321110001yfg`, then `16042321110002yfg`. The unique string contains time stamp, incremented number and 3 characters generated if the framework starts. For example:

```javascript
var user = { id: UID('users') };
var order = { id: UID('orders') };
var id = UID();
```

Creates a new transformation. This method is alias for `TransformBuilder.addTransform()`.

```javascript
// Creates a new transform
NEWTRANSFORM('uppercase', function(obj) {
    Object.keys(obj).forEach(function(key) {
        if (typeof(obj[key]) === 'string')
            obj[key] = obj[key].toUpperCase();
    });
    return obj;
});


var transformed = TRANSFORM('uppercase', { firstname: 'peter', lastname: 'Å¡irka' });
console.log(transformed);```

