Adds some `SchemaDeclaration` operation as a next operation after current operation in chaining `SchemaInstance.$async()`.

```javascript
$.next('workflow', 'send');

// or
$.next('workflow', 'send', { some_key: 'with custom options' });

// or
$.next('save', { rewrite: true, message: 'this is custom options' });```
It's alias for `$.model.$next()`.

Adds some `SchemaDeclaration` operation onto end of chaining of `SchemaInstance.$async()`.

```javascript
$.push('workflow', 'send');

// or
$.push('workflow', 'send', { some_key: 'with custom options' });

// or
$.push('save', { rewrite: true, message: 'this is custom options' });```
It's alias for `$.model.$push()`.

The method returns a value from multiple async operations from the same schema.

```javascript
// Returns all responses
$.response();

// Returns a response at 0 position
$.response(0);

// Returns a response at 1 position
$.response(1);

// +v3.4.4
// Returns a response from workflow "exec"
$.response('workflow.exec');

// +v3.4.4
// Returns a response from "save" operation
$.response('save');```

Can create a chaining for multiple operations. If some operation fills error then chaining is stopped and "callback" will be executed with this error. Response `index` can be changed in some operation, more info here `SchemaInstance.$output()`.

```javascript
// Response will contain all results
$.$async(function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
}).$save({ all: true }).$workflow('send').$transform('xml');

// Response will contain a result from "workflow"
$.$async(function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
}, 1).$save({ all: true }).$workflow('send').$transform('xml');```

It can be used for one-line async operations. It returns `SUCCESS()` result if the callback doesn't return error. A simple usage: 

```javascript
// Returns SUCCESS(true)
NOSQL('users').remove().where('id', '9289').callback($.done());
// Output will be without value: { success: true }

// Returns SUCCESS(true, response_from_callback)
NOSQL('users').remove().where('id', '9289').callback($.done(true));
// Output will be a value from DB: { success: true, value: RESULT_FROM_DB }

NOSQL('users').remove().where('id', '9289').callback($.done({ removed: true }));
// +v3.3.0 Output will be: { success: true, value: { removed: true }}```

Fast and simple error handling. It wraps this code `$.error.push()` and executes `$.callback()` immediately. A simple usage: 

```javascript
if (!$.model.terms) {
    $.invalid('terms', 'You must agree with terms and conditions.');
    return;
}```

It can write/read a value from model repository (internal meta-data repository contains each SchemaInstance object). A simple usage: 

```javascript
// Writing
$.repository('custom', 'value');

// Reading
console.log($.repository('custom'));```

api.body:
`Chunker` is a very helpful tool for storing temporary data when you are importing some data from another services or databases. It can store defined count of documents/data (serialized in JSON) per file and after import is done you can browse data step-by-step. `Chunker` is defined in `FrameworkUtils` and here is a simple usage:

```javascript
var chunker = U.chunker('products', 50);

// chunker === instance

somestream.on('data', U.streamer('<product>', '</product>', function(value, index) {
	var product = value.parseXML();

	// The chunker creates multiple files with a maximum count of chunks (in this case: 50 products)
	chunker.write(product);

	// Here we can't wait for DB because data are flowing in this time
}));

somestream.on('end', function() {

	// Flushs buffer
	chunker.end();

	chunker.each(function(items, next, index) {

		console.log(chunker.percentage);

		// here we can update DB

		// ....
		// ....

		// Read next items
		next();

	}, function() {

		// This method is called if the chunker doesn't contain any other items (optional).

		// Cleans up hdd (removes files) and memory
		chunker.destroy();
	});

});
```

__IMPORTANT__:
Chunker stores items to different files. A chunker `name` is a name of the file. If the chunker is destroyed then it removes all files automatically.

`+v3.1.0` __DataReader__ is very effective and optimized solution for reading and filtering data in real-time. With this solution you can stream data and filter data easily. Also NoSQL embedded database uses `DataReader` too.

```javascript
var reader = U.reader();

reader.find().between('price', 10, 200).callback(console.log);

// or
reader.scalar('max', 'price').callback(console.log);

// or
reader.count().between('price', 10, 200).callback(console.log);

// Some ReadStream
somestream.on('data', function(chunk) {
	// some data processing
	reader.push(ARRAY_OF_DOCS_or_DOC);
});

somestream.on('end', () => reader.done());```

`+v3.3.1` __FLOWSTREAM__ (currently beta) contains a small modified core of real Total.js Flow. You need to understand how it works. __The Flow can be used for__ e.g. Workflows, Alarms, Rule engines, etc..

- [Flow UI component](https://componentator.com/components/j-flow/) fully optimized for this Total.js Flow
- [Example](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/flow)

### `FLOWSTREAM()` method

Total.js Flow is optimized for different cases and you can provide different Flows in the same time.

```javascript
var flow1 = FLOWSTREAM(); // is same as FLOWSTREAM('default');
var flow2 = FLOWSTREAM('mails');
var flow3 = FLOWSTREAM('users');

// ...
// ...

flow1.trigger('id1__0', YOUR_INPUT_DATA);
```

Method `FLOWSTREAM()` creates a `Flow` instance if the instance doesn't exist. If the instance already exists then the method returns existing instance. You can provide unlimited count of Flow instances. First of all you have to register your components via `flow.register()` method, then you have to load Flow schema via `flow.use()`. After that you need to perform `flow.trigger()` for executing of Flow. 

### How does the Flow work?

Flow processes data according to the Flow schema. Flow Schema contains items. Each item contains its `connections` (output to input) to other items. You have to understand the schema below:

```javascript
{
	id1: {                    // ID of instance of the component
		component: 'trigger', // Type of component
		connections: [
			'0': {            // 0 means output index
				id: 'id2',    // target component ID
				index: 0      // target component input index: 0
			},
			'2': {            // 2 means output index
				id: 'id4',    // target component ID
				index: 2      // target component input index: 2
			}
		]
	},
	id2: {                    // ID of instance of the component
		component: 'SMS',     // Type of component
		connections: [
			'0': {            // 0 means output index
				id: 'id8',    // target component ID
				index: 1      // target component input index: 1
			},
			'2': {            // 2 means output index
				id: 'id3',    // target component ID
				index: 0      // target component input index: 0
			}
		]
	},
	...
}
```

Flow reads the schema above into the memory and the schema will react on incoming data. Incoming data must be executed via `flow.trigger()`, everything starts there.

### FlowMessage

Flow message is the most important part of Total.js Flow. Message will contain all data and you will work with the message instance only.

```javascript
// PROPERTIES
message.data                    // {Object} A message data
message.from;                   // {FlowComponent} A component instance
message.fromid;                 // {String} ID of component instance
message.fromindex;              // {Number} Output index
message.fromcomponent;          // {String} A component name
message.fromschema;             // {FlowSchema} A schema instance
message.to;                     // {FlowComponent} A component instance
message.toid;                   // {String} ID of component instance
message.toindex;                // {Number} Input index
message.tocomponent;            // {FlowComponent} A component name
message.toschema                // {FlowComponent} A schema instance
message.schema;                 // {FlowSchema} alias to "toschema"
message.cache;                  // {Object} A persistent cache for all messages and each instance of component
message.options;                // {Object} A custom options for the component
message.used;                   // {Number} How many components have processed the message?
message.repo;                   // {Object} A persistent cache for the current message
message.main;                   // {Flow} A flow instance
message.count;                  // {Number} A count of all processed messages per Flow
message.duration;               // {Number} Contains a creation date (ticks)
message.duration2;              // {Number} Contains a cloned date (ticks)
message.controller;             // {Controller} Total.js Controller (if exists)
message.user;                   // {Controller.user}
message.session;                // {Controller.session}
message.sessionid;              // {Controller.sessionid}
message.language;               // {Controller.language}
message.id;                     // {Controller.id}
message.ip;                     // {Controller.ip}
message.req;                    // {Controller.req}
message.res;                    // {Controller.res}
message.params;                 // {Controller.params}
message.files;                  // {Controller.files}
message.body;                   // {Controller.body}
message.query;                  // {Controller.query}
message.headers;                // {Controller.headers}
message.ua;                     // {Controller.ua} Contains parsed User-Agent

// METHODS
message.replace(NEW_DATA);

message.send(OUTPUT_INDEX);
// Sends the message next
// @OUTPUT_INDEX {String/Number} optional, sends the message to specific index (if the index isn't specified then the message will be sent to all outputs)
// return {Number} with count of outputs

message.destroy();
// Destroys the message

message.on('message', function(message) {
	// The message has been sent
});

message.on('end', function(message) {
	// The message has been destroyed
});
```

### FlowComponent

`FlowComponent` means a scope defined below:

```javascript
flow.register('component_name', function(exports) {

	// exports "means" FlowComponent instance

	// Delegates:

	exports.install = function() {

	};

	exports.uninstall = function() {

	};

	exports.message = function(message) {

	};

	exports.destroy = function() {

	};

	// +v3.3.0 supports "options" delegate:
	exports.options = function(options) {

	};

	// Properties:

	// exports.cache; {Object}
	// exports.disabled {Boolean}
	// exports.connected {Boolean}
	// exports.stats {Object} { pending: Number, input: Number, output: Number, duration: Number }

});
```

- Flow doesn't create instance for each type of component
- Each component has only the one instance
- `FlowComponent` instance depends on the `FlowMessage` only
- `FlowMessage` contains all data and meta data (e.g. `options`) for the component

### FlowSchema

`FlowSchema` contains a component evaluated data from the schema defined via `flow.use()`, example:

```javascript
component: 'trigger',
connections: [
	'0': {
		id: 'id2',
		index: 0
	},
	'2': {
		id: 'id4',
		index: 2
	}
]
```

So if you use custom data in the schema, then you can use it in the Flow.

### Example

We belive that you understand the example below. Just create a script called `flow.js` and run it.

```javascript
var flow = FLOWSTREAM();

flow.register('transform', function(exports) {

	exports.message = function(message) {
		switch (message.options.type) {
			case 'uppercase':
				message.data = message.data.toUpperCase();
				break;
			case 'lowercase':
				message.data = message.data.toLowerCase();
				break;
		}

		// Send next
		message.send(0);
	};

}, { type: 'uppercase' });

flow.register('reverse', function(exports) {
	exports.message = function(message) {

		var arr = message.data.split('');
		arr.reverse();
		message.data = arr.join('');

		message.send(0);
	};
});

flow.register('length', function(exports) {
	exports.message = function(message) {
		message.data = message.data.length;
		message.send(0);
	};
});

flow.register('debug', function(exports) {
	exports.message = function(message) {
		console.log(message.data);
		message.destroy();
	};
});

flow.use({

	com1: {
		component: 'transform',
		options: { type: 'uppercase' },
		connections: {
			'0': [
				{ id: 'com2', index: 0 },
				{ id: 'com3', index: 0 },
				{ id: 'com4', index: 0 }
			]
		}
	},
	com2: {
		component: 'length',
		connections: {
			'0': [
				{ id: 'com4', index: 0 }
			]
		}
	},
	com3: {
		component: 'reverse',
		connections: {
			'0': [
				{ id: 'com4', index: 0 }
			]
		}
	},
	com4: {
		component: 'debug'
	}
});

flow.trigger('com1__0', 'Total.js Platform');```

