## The module definition

### PROPERTY: exports.dependencies;

`optional` Can contain only array of Total.js module names. The framework waits for all dependencies.

```javascript
exports.dependencies = ['moduleA', 'moduleC'];
```

### METHOD: exports.install;

`optional` `important` This is the initialization function of the module. This function is executed if the framework loads modules. __Modules support routing.__ Argument: `options` can contain custom settings for the module and it's optional.

```javascript
exports.install = function(options) {
	console.log('Hello from the module.');
	ROUTE('/module/');
};
```

### METHOD: exports.uninstall;

`optional` This function is executed if the framework uninstalls the module. Argument: `options` can contain custom settings for the module, it's optional.

```javascript
exports.uninstall = function(options) {
	console.log('This module is uninstalled.');
};
```

### METHOD: exports.usage;

`optional` This function has to return a usage of the module. [Example: Usage](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/framework-usage).

```javascript
exports.usage = function() {
	return { requests: counter };
};
```

### A full example of the module

Filename: `modules/counter.js`

```javascript
exports.version = '1.01';

var counter = 0;

exports.install = function(options) {
	ON('request', increment);
	ROUTE('/stats/', json_stats);
};

exports.uninstall = function(options) {
	OFF('request', increment);
};

exports.usage = function() {
	return { requests: counter };
}

function json_stats() {
	// The same behavior like in the controller
	this.json({ requests: counter });
}

function increment() {
	counter++;
}
```

