## Parts

`+v3.3.0` supports Parts. Parts are very helpful if you want to render some group of components and you can choose different parts in the view where will be parts of components rendered.

__Example__:

```html
A component content.

@{part header}
	HEADER
@{end}

@{part footer}
	FOOTER
@{end}

<script total>
	exports.group = 'cms';
</script>
```

__Usage in views__:

```html
<header>
	<!-- Here will be rendered all parts of components which contain part "header" -->
	@{part('header')}
</header>

<main>
	BLA BLA
</main>

<footer>
	<!-- Here will be rendered all parts of components which contain part "footer" -->
	@{part('footer')}
</footer>

@{components('cms')}
```

## Good to know

### Inline files

Total.js `v3.0.0` supports component's inline files. The framework parses all inline files and stores them in the temporary directory. All files are available on `http://hostname.com/~componentname/filename.ext`. For example `myfirstcomponent.html`:

```html
<file name="logo.svg">base64</file>
<file name="template.html">base64</file>

<!-- +v3.3.0 supports custom encoding -->
<!-- Default encoding is "base64" -->
<file name="template2.html" encoding="utf8">
YOUR HTML CODE
</file>

<!-- Renders a logo from this component -->
<img src="/~myfirstcomponent/logo.svg" />

<script total>
    ...
</script>
```

### Static files according to group name

Total.js `v2.7.0` supports rendering of specific scripts/styles for component's group, for example:

```html
@{components('dashboard')}
@{components('flowboard')}
```

__The framework will render__:

```html
<head>
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="/components.css?group=dashboard&version=1498544518093" />
	<script src="/components.js?group=dashboard&version=1498544518093"></script>
	<link rel="stylesheet" href="/components.css?group=flowboard&version=1498544518093" />
	<script src="/components.js?group=flowboard&version=1498544518093"></script>
</head>
```

If the view contains `@{component()}` the framework renders static files (js+css) from all registered components.

### Hash

Because of HTTP cache, if the framework registers a new component it changes version hash. Therefore your `components.css` and `components.js` have still another hash e.g. `?version=ak38s`.

### Renaming of static files

You can rename static files `.css` and `.js` of components via config file:

__Default settings__:

```html
static-url-components    : /components.
```

__You can change it to e.g.__:

```html
static-url-components    : /components/all.
```

__The result will be:__
- `/components/all.js`
- `/components/all.css`

Total.js has a simple authorization mechanism. It's built on one delegate function `AUTH(function)`. The authorization is asynchronous.

- You can create your own authorization mechanism (Total.js gives open options).
- The authorization delegate is async.
- You can authorize users according to the cookies / headers.
- You can set user roles.
- The authorization delegate adds `authorize` and `unauthorize` flag according to the state.
- Is executed in each request.
- __Delegate does not handle static files.__
- [Example: authorization](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/authorization)
---

![Authorization](resources/authorization.png)

---

`+v3.3.0` brings great new improvements.

## A simple example

Create e.g. definition:

```javascript
AUTH(function($) {

	// $ means "AuthOptions"

	// ====================================
	// Properties:
	// ====================================

	// $.req;
	// $.res;

	// $.flags;
	// {String Array} A custom flags

	// $.headers;
	// {Object} Reads request headers

	// $.ip;
	// {String} Reads IP address

	// $.language;
	// {String} Reads language

	// $.query;
	// {Object} Reads query values

	// $.filter;
	// {Object} Reads prepared query arguments according to the query schema (+v3.3.0)

	// $.params;
	// {Object} Reads URL dynamic params

	// $.ua;
	// {String} Returns parsed User-Agent (+v3.4.0)

	// ====================================
	// Methods:
	// ====================================

	// $.invalid([user_instance]);
	// Doesn't authorize user (it will be unauthorized)

	// $.success(user_instance);
	// Authorizes the user (it will be authorized)

	// $.done();
	// returns function(err, user) for handling callbacks

	// $.cookie(name);
	// Reads a cookie

	// $.roles(role1, role2, roleN);
	// Appends roles for the current user

	// $.cookie(name, value, expires, [options]);
	// Creates a cookie

	// EXAMPLE:
	var userId = ($.cookie('user') || '').parseInt();

	if (userId === 0) {
		// unauthorized user
		$.invalid();
		return;
	}

	var nosql = NOSQL('users');

	nosql.one().where('id', userId).callback(function(err, user) {

		if (err || !user) {
			// unauthorized user
			$.invalid();
			return;
		}

		// user is authorized
		$.success(user);
	});
});
```

Usage in controllers:

```javascript
exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('/user/', view_logged,   ['authorize']);
	ROUTE('/user/', view_unlogged, ['unauthorize']);
}

function view_logged() {
	this.view('logged');
}

function view_unlogged() {
	this.view('unlogged');}```

Schemas are a big part of Total.js framework. With schemas you can control incoming data and convert them to your defined types. Each schema can support validation and multiple operations (CRUD operations, transformations, workflows or hooks) which you can call step-by-step.

## Creating schemas

A schema describes a data-types/data-structure for incoming data only and __schema isn't a mirror for database table schema__. So we define a simple schema `User` which we use on this page:

```javascript
NEWSCHEMA('User', function(schema) {

	// Define fields in the schema
	// schema.define('FIELD_NAME', 'DATA_TYPE', [required]);

	schema.define('firstname', 'Capitalize(30)', true);
	schema.define('lastname', 'Capitalize(30)', true);
	schema.define('age', Number, age => age >= 18);

	// Sets a default value
	schema.define('age', Number)(18);

	// Define operations in the schema
	// BTW: all operations below are optional

	schema.setQuery(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		$.success();
	});

	schema.setGet(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		$.success();
	});

	schema.setInsert(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		// $.model ==> data
		$.success();
	});

	schema.setUpdate(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		// $.model ==> data
		$.success();
	});

	schema.setRemove(function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		$.success();
	});

	schema.addWorkflow('logoff', function($) {
		// $ ==> is SchemaOptions
		// your code
		$.success();
	});

	// etc..

});
```

Framework converts incoming data according to the schema __always__. So you __always__ get type as you defined. Default values:

- `array` returns `[]`
- `boolean` returns `false`
- `date` returns `new Date()`
- `json` returns `''`
- `number` returns `0`
- `number2` returns `null`
- `object` returns `null`
- `string` returns `''`
- `email` returns `'@'`
- link to schema returns `null`

__Good to know__:

- schema doesn't need to contain defined operations
- schema doesn't need to contain defined fields (e.g. you want to use operations only)
- all [schema data-types](#)
- methods and properties in [SchemaOptions](#)
- methods in [SchemaInstance](#)

---

## Dictionary

### SchemaDeclaration

