## Live reloading

The client-side script tries to connect via WebSocket to `ws://127.0.0.1:35729`. Total.js `debugging` mode (in Total.js `+v3.0.0`) creates a WebSocket listener and if some file is changed then it sends to all listeners a message for reloading a browser.

### How do I enable `livereload` on client-side?

- Source-code: <https://github.com/totaljs/livereload>
- CDN script: `https://cdn.totaljs.com/livereload.js` (only __400 bytes__ without GZIP compression)

__Just append this script to your website:__

```html
<html>
	<head>
	</head>
	<body>

		Your HTML code.

		<!-- LIVE RELOAD SCRIPT -->
		<script src="https://cdn.totaljs.com/livereload.js"></script>

		<!-- OR WITH A CUSTOM URL -->
		<script src="https://cdn.totaljs.com/livereload.js" data-url="ws://livereload.totaljs.com"></script>

	</body>
</html>
```

### How do I enable `livereload` in Total.js app?

Live reload works only with Total.js `+v3.0.0`. So just update your `debug.js` file like this:

```javascript
const options = {};

// (Optinal) custom IP
// options.ip = '127.0.0.1';

// (Optinal) custom port
// options.port = parseInt(process.argv[2]);

// (Optional) Overwrites config
// options.config = { name: 'Total.js' };

// (Optional) Sleeps the
// options.sleep = 3000;

// (Optional) Enables Google Chrome code inspector on the port below:
// options.inspector = 9229;

// (Optional) Your own custom directories in the application's root:
// options.watch = ['adminer'];

// !!! HERE !!!
// !!! HERE !!!
// !!! HERE !!!
// (Optional) Enables live reloading
options.livereload = true;

require('total.js/debug')(options);
```

And run it `$ node debug.js`. That's all.

---

__Good to know__:

- livereload uses port `35729` with hostname `127.0.0.1`
- it works with Total.js apps only!!!
- you can feel a small delay
- __important__ you can work with only the one instance of Total.js app and livereload feature
- `+v3.3.0` performing `process.send('total:restart')` in the app will restart the app in debug mode only
- `+v3.4.0` works with cluster

In Total.js `+v2.7.0` the Unit-Testing mechanism has been updated.

## How the test has to be look?

- each `test` has to be stored in `/your-app/tests/` directory
- `tests` directory can contain sub-directories with tests
- `test` is executed if the framework is fully started

```javascript
// Testing method:
TEST('Test method', function() {
	$GET('Users', 100, function(err, response) {
		FAIL(err != null);
		// or
		// OK(err == null);
	});
});

// Testing controller's action
TEST('Test action', '/api/newsletter/', function(builder) {
	builder.json({ email: 'petersirka@gmail.com' });
	builder.exec(function(err, response) {
		FAIL(response.success !== true);
		// or
		// OK(respons.success);
	});
});
```

## How to run tests?

- create `/you-app/test.js` file with this content:

```javascript
// Debug mode:
require('total.js').http('test debug');

// Release mode:
// require('total.js').http('test');
```

__Terminal__:

```bash
$ node test.js
```

## Troubleshooting

### Can I have multiple `FAIL()` or `OK()` method in a row?

- Yes.

### How can I add additional description to test?

```javascript
FAIL(err != null, 'error handling');
FAIL(user != null, 'checking user instance');
OK(response.success, 'email validation');
```

### Can I have tests in different sub-directories?

- Yes.

### Can I do a fake authorization?

Yes, `+v3.0.0` supports new method `TESTUSER(userObject, [flags])` which wraps `AUTH()` delegate. Just append this method before your `TEST()` method.

```javascript
// without flags
TESTUSER({ id: 1, name: 'Peter Širka' });

// or with flags:
TESTUSER({ id: 1, name: 'Peter Širka' }, ['@admin']);

// returns back older "F.onAuthorize" delegate
TESTUSER();```
